owAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=123.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ToVN Rotation agreement/rules</span><hr size=1> Firstly, please don't make light of how much effort it takes to clear from the zone in, break the Rampage Wyverns, kill Ikky because its your turn, and then have to back off while another guild takes its Eashen turn, so that you can return, rebreak into N ToV and then continue on to deal with Aaryonar and the rest of N ToV.  It's not just &quot;going to ToV twice instead of once&quot;.  It's a major hassle.  Saying that these mobs don't affect N ToV just isn't true.  It becomes a guild planning nightmare, especially with the varied play times.  Imagine if VoF has to wait for NB to kill Ikky on our turn, so you can get Eashen on yours.  Then we have to wait for you to kill Eashen for us to get Aaryonar.  Already you have added 2 days to the length of time needed to clear N ToV.<br>
<br>
You can't put Eashen and Ikky on their own duo rotation, because not every guild can who can kill Ikky can kill Eashen.  Thus it becomes &quot;unfair&quot; to other guilds who can kill Ikky but not Eashen (by virtue of your own argument that the present N ToV rotation isn't fair to you).  Keeping all of N ToV together is consistent, geographically defineable, and is open to all guilds who can meet the requirements.  The same line is being drawn, just a matter of where - you say Ikky and Eashen, I say all of N ToV by killing Aaryonar (as the rotation has been for a year).<br>
<br>
Secondly, this starts a horrible precedent that Thaldin alludes to.  The hardest dragon in N ToV is Vyemm, the second is Aaryonar.  Many of the rest are between Gozzrem and Dozekar level.  I for one don't want to see 14 new rotations that all depend on who has cleared what.  Suddenly NB is up for Lady Mirenella, Sevelak and Vyemm, but can't touch Koi, Cekenar or Aaryonar, because other guilds are up for those.  It would make N ToV a nightmare, both for the guilds who think they want something like this, and those of us who have actually cleared there and know how bad it would be to clear with a myriad of other guilds in those halls.<br>
<br>
Then there is the question of loot quality vs time invested.  By the time a guild is capable of killing Vyemm and Aaryonar, the loot obtained runs the gamut from amazing (4-5 items) to incredibly pathetic (Beldryn's Bane anyone? What IS an 11/24 1hb that you can get in Howling Stones, doing in N ToV anyway?!).  The whole of a N ToV raid is between 7 and 14 hours once you get used to it.  The only thing that balances it out and makes it worthwhile to do is the 2-4 loots times 14 mobs (and of those only 2-5 will be really &quot;worth it&quot; items once you are full Kael/Skyshrine).  Remove two of these mobs times 2-4 items, and it just lessened how worthwhile it is.  If you doubt my assessment of the loot quality, please note BOTS has been inactive on the N ToV rotation for months, but STILL participates in Statue, King Tormax and Avatar of War rotations.  Once you get on N ToV rotation (and you will, its just a matter of time), you will appreciate the same level of exclusivity for your time investment, for the same reason that we have planar reservations.  Few raids are better than knowing everything in Area X are you and your friend's purvey and no one will come stomping in and messing things up.<br>
<br>
The reason Aaryonar is used as the &quot;gauge&quot; mob is because other than Vyemm he is arguably the hardest (Lady Nev can be annoying too) and most necessary.  If you don't kill Aaryonar, you can't get any other dragons no matter how you slice it.  Past Aaryonar, access to easier mobs (like Ikky and Eashen).  Without Aaryonar being dead, these guilds would never have access to them.  That is why Verant nerfed the CoH spot near the back 5, so people couldnt take advantage like this.  So a multiple rotation N ToV wouldn't work, as only three guilds would be on the Aaryonar and Vyemm rotations, and there would be 4+ on the other 12.  All that would need to happen is those three guilds not to kill Aaryonar, and all other rotations further in would be moot.<br>
<br>
So to sum up, I disagree with making Ikky and Eashen a separate rotation(s) from N ToV for the following reasons:<br>
1.  Breaking into N ToV is more than just &quot;coming back twice instead of once&quot;.<br>
2.  A duo Ikky and Eashen rotation would be just as &quot;unfair&quot; as the current N ToV rotation as some guilds could kill Ikky but not Eashen.  Same line, just where do you draw it.  Historically it was drawn geographically, and its been a fair way to do it.<br>
3.  Bad precedent leading to a new 14 rotation N ToV.<br>
4.  Having multiple guilds in N ToV at once is asking for headaches, problems, and inconveniences.  Same would be said for having to come back multiple times for multiple mobs you are up for.  Administrative and guild planning nightmare.<br>
5.  Breaking up the N ToV rotation makes it more difficult and less worthwhile for all guilds in said rotations.  Think planar raids as a guild vs planar camps.  (Druid LFG for gorgon group, have starfire!)<br>
6.  While Aaryonar is harder than Eashen and Ikky, he is also harder than most of the remaining dragons.  Killing him gets you access to lots of easier mobs, all in one geographic area.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
